  "diary": "Woke up early enough to catch the thrift store before the day got weird. The transit strike had everyone panicking, but I figured it out—just biked to the studio through the back streets of Fremont. The morning was solid; back-to-back consults and a sleeve session that actually felt right. Grabbed lunch at Fuel around eleven, needed the caffeine hit honestly.\n\nAfternoon flew by with more work. I was hyper-aware of the clock, not wanting to get stuck in surge pricing hell if I had to rideshare home. Ended up just walking and biking back to Belltown once the strike lifted. Showered off the stencil ink, made some dinner, then got lost in chess puzzles for a couple hours. Found a killer vintage band tee at the thrift haul from this morning. Felt pretty grounded by evening.",
  "thought_process": "The transit strike actually worked in my favor—it forced me to be intentional about my route and timing instead of just defaulting to the usual. I stayed focused on work because there was a natural endpoint, and I didn't want to risk getting stranded or paying ridiculous surge prices. The thrift stop was pure habit, but I needed that small ritual before work. By afternoon, knowing the strike would lift by 4pm, I felt less rushed. I chose to bike home instead of rideshare because it felt cheaper and clearer. The evening felt earned—I was tired but satisfied, so the chess puzzles and just sitting with my stuff felt right. Good day overall.",
